{
  "Question": "<blockquote> <p>Given an infinite field <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_902\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"K\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>K</mi> </math></span>, one can prove that any maximal ideal of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_903\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"K[X,Y]\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>K</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> can't be principal. In fact, every non-principal prime ideal is a maximal ideal, and can be generated by two polynomials.</p> <p>I am wondering whether the same result holds in <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_904\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\mathbb F_{q}[X,Y]\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span>. Can we find a principal ideal <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_905\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"I=(P(X,Y))\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>I</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <mi>P</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> for some irreducible polynomial <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_906\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>P</mi> </math></span> that is a maximal ideal ?  </p> </blockquote> <p>Such a polynomial <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_907\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>P</mi> </math></span> must have positive degrees in both <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_908\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"X\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>X</mi> </math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_909\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"Y\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>Y</mi> </math></span>. Indeed, given an irreducible polynomial <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_910\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"Q(X)\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>Q</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> in only one variable, the quotient  <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_911\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\mathbb F_{q}[X,Y]/(Q(X))\\cong(\\mathbb F_{q}[X]/(Q(X)))[Y]\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>/</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <mi>Q</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>\u2245</mo> <mrow> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>/</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <mi>Q</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> is a ring of polynomials over a field and as such, can never be a field.  </p> <p>Moreover, such a polynomial <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_912\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>P</mi> </math></span> must have the form  <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_913\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P(X,Y)=\\sum_{i=0}^{n}P_{i}(X)Y^{i}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>P</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <munderover> <mo largeop=\"true\" movablelimits=\"false\" symmetric=\"true\">\u2211</mo> <mrow> <mi>i</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> <mi>n</mi> </munderover> <mrow> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>i</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msup> <mi>Y</mi> <mi>i</mi> </msup> </mrow> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> where <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_914\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"d\\geq 1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>d</mi> <mo>\u2265</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math></span>, the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_915\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P_{i}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>i</mi> </msub> </math></span>'s are polynomials in <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_916\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"X\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>X</mi> </math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_917\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P_{n}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>n</mi> </msub> </math></span> is a nonzero polynomial that vanishes identically on <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_918\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\mathbb F_{q}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> </mrow> </math></span>, thus <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_919\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P_{n}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>n</mi> </msub> </math></span> must be divisible by <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_920\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\prod_{\\alpha\\in\\mathbb F_{q}}(X-\\alpha)\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <munder> <mo largeop=\"true\" movablelimits=\"false\" symmetric=\"true\">\u220f</mo> <mrow> <mi>\u03b1</mi> <mo>\u2208</mo> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> </mrow> </mrow> </munder> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <mi>X</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mi>\u03b1</mi> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span>.<br/> Indeed, if there were some <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_921\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\alpha\\in\\mathbb F_{q}\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>\u03b1</mi> <mo>\u2208</mo> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> such that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_922\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P_{n}(\\alpha)\\not=0\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mi>P</mi> <mi>n</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>\u03b1</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>\u2260</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </math></span>, then the ideal <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_923\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"I:=(P,X-\\alpha)\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>I</mi> <mo>:=</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>P</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mrow> <mi>X</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mi>\u03b1</mi> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> would contain <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_924\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"(P)\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>P</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </math></span> strictly. If <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_925\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"(P)\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>P</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </math></span> were to be maximal, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_926\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"I\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>I</mi> </math></span> would be the whole of <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_927\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\mathbb F_{q}[X,Y]\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span>. Writing down the fact that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_928\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"1\\in I\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mo>\u2208</mo> <mi>I</mi> </mrow> </math></span> and evaluating <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_929\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"X=\\alpha\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>X</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mi>\u03b1</mi> </mrow> </math></span> would leads us to the conclusion <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_930\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"n=\\deg_{Y}(P)=0\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <msub> <mi>deg</mi> <mi>Y</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2061</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>P</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>0</mn> </mrow> </math></span>, which is absurd.  </p> <p>This is all I could infer so far. With respect to the above, I tried looking at <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_931\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P(X,Y)=(X^{p-1}-1)XY-1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>P</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <msup> <mi>X</mi> <mrow> <mi>p</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>Y</mi> </mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> or <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_932\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"P(X,Y)=(X^{p-1}-1)XY-X-1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>P</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo> <mrow> <msup> <mi>X</mi> <mrow> <mi>p</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo> </mrow> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>Y</mi> </mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> in <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_933\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\mathbb F_{p}[X,Y]\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>p</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span> for some prime number <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_934\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"p\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>p</mi> </math></span> but I have trouble determining whether the quotient is a field or not.  </p> <p>Would somebody know the answer of the problem, and according to it, give a proof or a counter-example ? Thank you very much in advance.</p>",
  "Title": "Is there a principal maximal ideal in <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_901\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"\\mathbb F_{q}[X,Y]\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\mathbb</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <msub> <mi>F</mi> <mi>q</mi> </msub> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mrow> <mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo> <mi>X</mi> <mo>,</mo> <mi>Y</mi> <mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo> </mrow> </mrow> </math></span>?",
  "Tags": "polynomials,commutative-algebra,field-theory,finite-fields"
}